Explanation of how the Operation Object was derived:

- The controller method handling DELETE /admin/posts/{post} is App\Http\Controllers\Admin\PostController::destroy.
- The method signature is destroy(Post $post). This uses Laravel's route model binding to resolve the {post} path parameter to an instance of App\Models\Post (typically using an integer ID).
- The method calls $post->delete() and then returns redirect()->route('admin.posts.index')->withSuccess(...). That corresponds to an HTTP redirect response after successful deletion (commonly a 302).
- If the route model binding fails (no Post matches the provided identifier), Laravel will produce a 404 response.
- Based on the above, the Operation Object includes:
  - a summary and description reflecting deletion and redirect behavior,
  - a required path parameter "post" (integer id, resolved to App\Models\Post),
  - a 302 response with a Location header describing the redirect target,
  - a 404 response for not-found cases,
  - an operationId to uniquely identify the operation.

